What do you mean by File handling?

**File handling** in C++ simply means:

👉 **Reading data from files and writing data to files using your program**

Instead of only using console (`cin`, `cout`), your program can work with real files on disk.

---

# Why file handling matters (very practical)

With just this skill, you can build:

* Log analyzers
* Data processors (CSV, text files)
* Backup tools
* Simple databases (file-based)

This is how your “console C++” becomes useful in real work.

---

# Basic idea

A file is just like:

notes.txt
data.csv
log.txt

Your C++ program can:

* Open it
* Read from it
* Modify it
* Write back to it

---

# Core components in C++

You use the `<fstream>` library:

* `std::ifstream` → read file
* `std::ofstream` → write file
* `std::fstream` → read + write

---

# Example 1: Write to a file

#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>

int main() {
    std::ofstream file("data.txt");  // create/open file

    file << "Hello Shiv\n";
    file << "C++ file handling\n";

    file.close();  // always close
}

👉 This creates `data.txt` and writes content.

---

# Example 2: Read from a file

#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("data.txt");

    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        std::cout << line << std::endl;
    }

    file.close();
}

Reads line by line and prints to console.

---

# Example 3: Append to a file

std::ofstream file("data.txt", std::ios::app);
file << "New line added\n";

👉 Adds without deleting old data.

